one thing that I think is a really undervalued part of that process is thinking about what is,

00:43:10.399 --> 00:43:14.879
like, how will you know a good solution when you find one, and how would you know if it was a good

00:43:14.879 --> 00:43:19.760
solution if it was, like, staring you in the face and you already had it? I think the more

00:43:19.760 --> 00:43:27.520
unstructured and complicated a problem can be, it can almost be a little deceptive of what's good,

00:43:27.760 --> 00:43:32.479
what's good, which can have, like, one of two kind of, like, bad outcomes of either,

00:43:35.600 --> 00:43:38.560
you find a good solution, but you don't realize it's good, so you keep going,

00:43:39.280 --> 00:43:45.120
or you spend a lot of time, like, chasing after an outcome, and then you get there,

00:43:45.120 --> 00:43:49.280
and only then do you realize, like, I solved the problem I was trying to solve,

00:43:49.280 --> 00:43:55.520
it was not the problem I wanted to solve. So, something I've really been experimenting with

00:43:55.520 --> 00:44:00.879
in my own work is having a lot more of an explicit, like, design stage at the beginning

00:44:00.879 --> 00:44:06.639
of a project, and thinking, like, how can you do a pilot? How can you, like, you know,

00:44:06.639 --> 00:44:13.679
if I'm trying to predict some target, can I take those, like, true values of that target

00:44:13.679 --> 00:44:18.000
and plug them into a downstream problem I, like, actually thought that was going to solve,

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:21.840
and make sure that's actually what I want to solve? And almost kind of, like,

00:44:22.800 --> 00:44:28.719
front-loading model evaluation with a, even, like, fake solution is, like, the first step

00:44:28.719 --> 00:44:36.879
versus the last step. And then I'll attack on one other point, and sorry, I'm kind of rambling here,

00:44:36.879 --> 00:44:41.439
but I think the other aspect of that, just, again, going back to that levels of abstraction,

00:44:42.239 --> 00:44:49.040
is figuring out how to take the context out of my problem to make it something more Googleable.

00:44:49.040 --> 00:44:52.159
So, you know, I mean, thinking, like, not being, like,

00:44:54.560 --> 00:44:59.520
oh, this experiment, the random seeds were wrong, so I don't have a control population.

00:44:59.520 --> 00:45:03.040
What do I do? But then, like, backing that into more of a general, like,

00:45:04.560 --> 00:45:08.399
how do you sample a synthetic control from observational data, which is something you

00:45:08.399 --> 00:45:16.080
can Google and then find a ton of resources about. So, I think pushing myself on what I want,

00:45:16.080 --> 00:45:21.360
and then finding the right brain at which task for help.

00:45:23.840 --> 00:45:29.919
That's great. Thank you. Anas, I see you had a question. Do you want to jump in here next?

00:45:29.919 --> 00:45:35.439
Sure. So, Emily, I'm sure you've been in this position before, but any tips and advice

00:45:35.439 --> 00:45:39.520
on communicating to non-technical stakeholders and or leadership?

00:45:40.399 --> 00:45:47.439
Yeah, no, that's always a hot, like, enduring hot topic, and for very, very good reasons, I think.

00:45:48.159 --> 00:45:52.719
I think, like, a couple of different, I think, approaches that I tend to use there

00:45:53.840 --> 00:46:00.560
is, A, like, leading with the solution versus kind of, like, leading with the solution,

00:46:00.560 --> 00:46:06.800
leading with impact versus leading with that, like, kind of process. And I think as many people

00:46:07.280 --> 00:46:13.840
know, I'm a, like, huge R Markdown fan, and maybe now I should say quarto, but I've actually, like,

00:46:13.840 --> 00:46:19.120
come to the realization that I kind of need to even change my workflow for working with a tool

00:46:19.120 --> 00:46:25.520
like that because, like, inherently, like, an R Markdown workflow is kind of very linear of, like,

00:46:26.320 --> 00:46:31.600
I cleaned my data. I did the analysis. I got the outcome. But then from a storytelling perspective,

00:46:32.399 --> 00:46:37.520
I think you can really, like, get the hook and get the buy-in to, like, keep that conversation going

00:46:38.080 --> 00:46:42.959
if you lead more with the outcome of, like, this is why what I'm about to tell you is important.

00:46:44.800 --> 00:46:49.040
And then some people want to really dig deeper and understand the mechanics.

00:46:50.479 --> 00:46:57.439
Some people won't, and I think it's also as, like, data person learning to accept that that's okay

00:46:57.679 --> 00:47:02.639
that they don't, they don't want, like, like, I think all of us, it's very, like, it can really

00:47:02.639 --> 00:47:08.800
be about the journey versus the outcome, but accepting for, like, leaders, reasonably, it is

00:47:08.800 --> 00:47:16.239
often about the outcome. But then when I want to go into those details, I think I both either try

00:47:16.239 --> 00:47:25.520
to, like, lean heavily on both and or either of, like, metaphors and also, like, diagrams or one

00:47:25.520 --> 00:47:32.959
really compelling plot, just anything to make it more tangible versus, like, purely conceptual.

00:47:36.239 --> 00:47:42.159
Thank you. Thank you very much. I see, Lewis, you had a similar question as well.

00:47:43.439 --> 00:47:46.959
Do you have any follow-up questions or did that answer you as well?

00:47:49.840 --> 00:47:54.000
I guess maybe a follow-up and maybe it really is the same, just to clarify. I guess that in

00:47:54.000 --> 00:48:01.520
one sense makes it sound a communication kind of piece, but do you have the same answer if it's

00:48:02.159 --> 00:48:07.199
a brand new project or maybe a completely different approach? I don't mean a new

00:48:07.199 --> 00:48:11.520
quantitative approach, but maybe here's a stakeholder who's not really worked with

00:48:11.520 --> 00:48:17.919
quantitative people or maybe is wedded to a tool set. Maybe they use a business intelligence tool

00:48:17.919 --> 00:48:24.399
and you're advocating Shiny and it's interactive or something like that. So, to them, there's some

00:48:24.399 --> 00:48:30.000
kind of context, which even if, let's say, quantitatively there isn't, do you have any advice

00:48:31.199 --> 00:48:35.520
on how to advocate that and get the buy-in? And, of course, I imagine it's probably still

00:48:35.520 --> 00:48:40.560
a question of, here's why, what I'm about to tell you should be interesting or helpful, but do you

00:48:40.560 --> 00:48:44.560
have any anything else that's come up where you say this has really worked when I'm trying to

00:48:44.560 --> 00:48:52.879
advocate something new? Yeah, no, I think that's a great point of tools versus analyses

00:48:52.879 --> 00:49:00.159
because tools are so inherently abstract, it can't make it harder, but I do think

00:49:02.080 --> 00:49:07.439
probably how I've translated it, leaders inherently, I think, care a lot about

00:49:07.439 --> 00:49:13.120
the people on their team, hopefully from the genuinely caring perspective, but at least

00:49:13.120 --> 00:49:18.159
from the managing capacity perspective, bare minimum, and I think kind of

00:49:18.959 --> 00:49:25.520
leading with the case, I think most tools, you can also bring a human dimension

00:49:25.520 --> 00:49:32.479
into that story, whether it's such a pain point that people have to,

00:49:32.479 --> 00:49:37.280
they're doing this manual work every single month, then that's inhibiting both

00:49:37.280 --> 00:49:41.120
them doing more interesting projects in their career development, but there's a way to automate

00:49:41.120 --> 00:49:49.199
this thing, or like, hey, three months ago, we had this error and this breakdown in

00:49:49.199 --> 00:49:56.399
this process, and that's because we don't have good version control on GitHub, and

00:49:56.399 --> 00:50:02.560
I think always, you can tie it either to business outcomes or people outcomes,

00:50:03.360 --> 00:50:10.399
but I always, I think, try to anchor more to what does any tool do for you,

00:50:11.520 --> 00:50:17.199
and there's a broader framework that I really like for thinking about this called the

00:50:17.199 --> 00:50:22.320
jobs to be done framework that kind of comes from the product management world,

00:50:23.199 --> 00:50:28.560
and essentially what that says is you can think about a tool as someone you're

00:50:28.560 --> 00:50:33.600
hiring to do a job, and I'm kind of saying it at a trivially high level, I think

00:50:33.600 --> 00:50:37.360
there's more to the actual theory, but I've always liked that,

00:50:41.120 --> 00:50:45.199
kind of framework for, like, thinking about the interview, thinking about, like, why should I,

00:50:45.199 --> 00:50:50.479
like, bother to, like, hire and onboard you, and is this tool more, like, almost going back

00:50:50.479 --> 00:50:55.360
to the AI discussion, is this, like, an intern that I only want to use with a very high level

00:50:55.360 --> 00:51:01.760
of supervision, or if you're thinking about CICD and process automation, it's, like, am I hiring

00:51:01.760 --> 00:51:08.000
an executive or a contractor to just go run this process for me in an abstracted way,

00:51:08.879 --> 00:51:12.159
and I think that's, like, that framework, I think it's really kind of,

00:51:14.719 --> 00:51:19.120
whether it's implicit or explicit, helped kind of my, like, storytelling around those

00:51:19.120 --> 00:51:24.719
technical tools also. Very cool. Thank you. Thank you very helpful.

00:51:26.639 --> 00:51:33.280
Thank you. So I see we have a few minutes left here, and I think still quite a few

00:51:34.159 --> 00:51:37.280
questions here, so I'm going to go and try and go through some of these quickly.

00:51:38.000 --> 00:51:43.840
But I see Bill had asked, he said, I'm in pharma, but wonder if there are trends,

00:51:44.560 --> 00:51:51.439
blessed by management, to move away from some alternative software, which is how Bill

00:51:51.439 --> 00:51:58.879
says SaaS, but maybe more broadly, like, are there trends from your leadership, like,

00:51:58.879 --> 00:52:03.600
moving towards open source, or do you have free reign over the tools that you get to use?

00:52:04.560 --> 00:52:09.840
So I'm, like, definitely feel really lucky to be in an environment that's, like, pretty much

00:52:09.840 --> 00:52:16.000
always been very, very friendly to open source, and I think that is, like, I know a trend I've

00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:21.679
seen across the industry. I've had the opportunity also to do some consulting projects with other

00:52:21.679 --> 00:52:34.000
people, more into biostats and pharma fields, taking that leap to, I'd copy Bill's very

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:40.719
diplomatic phrasing if I could, but other proprietary options to the R world.

00:52:42.320 --> 00:52:47.280
And especially, I mean, I can only imagine, I think, the intersection of data tooling

00:52:48.000 --> 00:52:52.959
with the current, like, economic conditions, I have to imagine can only, like, kind of

00:52:52.959 --> 00:52:58.639
accelerate that trend when it's becoming an increasingly, like, easy to hire skill set,

00:52:59.760 --> 00:53:09.040
much more attractive option through the bottom line. And I think that gains that have been made

00:53:09.040 --> 00:53:15.360
in adoption in both, like, banking and finance, as well as, like, healthcare, really put a lot

00:53:15.360 --> 00:53:21.439
more of a rubber stamp of approval on some version of open source in really highly regulated

00:53:21.439 --> 00:53:30.239
industries. Thank you. And Amrit, I see you had a question about transitioning into data science

00:53:30.239 --> 00:53:35.520
roles. Do you want to jump in here? Yeah, thank you, and hi, Emily.

00:53:37.439 --> 00:53:43.760
Yeah, I, so my, like, basic question was that I'm just transitioning into data science roles,

00:53:43.760 --> 00:53:49.120
or I'm looking for data science roles. So I was just wondering, are there any considerations I

00:53:49.120 --> 00:54:01.600
should be having while interviewing with companies and in terms of, you know, maximizing my capacity

00:54:01.600 --> 00:54:08.000
to learn in that company? Because, like, I'll just give you some more context. I was just

00:54:08.000 --> 00:54:13.120
talking to one of my friends who is in the healthcare space, and she was saying she's

00:54:13.120 --> 00:54:17.439
working as a data scientist, but then she was saying that a lot of her time goes into

00:54:18.479 --> 00:54:26.879
data processing rather than actually having to, being able to get any inferences out of data or

00:54:26.879 --> 00:54:34.959
being able to do any kind of predictive work. So yeah, I was just wondering if there are any

00:54:34.959 --> 00:54:41.760
considerations I should be having, or if this is a non-question, I'm really not sure. Yeah,

00:54:41.760 --> 00:54:49.199
no, I mean, I think there's three aspects I'd say to that. I think first, definitely, like,

00:54:49.199 --> 00:54:54.320
can be really helpful to understand, like, a company's tech stack when you're interviewing

00:54:54.320 --> 00:54:59.040
and the amount of data they have available that you don't want to be, like, hired to be a data

00:54:59.040 --> 00:55:05.280
scientist and then show up on day one and have them be, like, oh yeah, here's a Google Drive

00:55:05.280 --> 00:55:09.919
with some CSVs in it, like, go wild. You know, I mean, you want to be sure they have, like,

00:55:10.000 --> 00:55:15.280
enough data to support analysis and that either you'll be empowered to have the tools to build

00:55:15.280 --> 00:55:21.280
out the data you need yourself, or maybe they also have, like, data engineering or other job functions.

00:55:22.719 --> 00:55:28.239
Secondly, I think it's helpful to be crisp about what you want to learn and grow on in a role.

00:55:28.239 --> 00:55:32.959
Like, data science can be such a nebulous job title these days. You know, I mean, I think

00:55:32.959 --> 00:55:38.800
someplace, like, it can mean anything from BI, experimentation, modeling, machine learning,

00:55:39.360 --> 00:55:46.800
and I think really just clarifying your interests and then just being able to, like, articulate them.

00:55:46.800 --> 00:55:52.479
Like, companies, like, do not have any incentive to, like, hire you for a role you don't want,

00:55:52.479 --> 00:55:55.760
so I think, like, kind of being able to, like, share what you're looking for

00:55:57.040 --> 00:56:02.959
really just helps the matchmaking. But finally, I think it's also really good to recognize, like,

00:56:03.040 --> 00:56:07.439
you can learn a ton in pretty much any role, and I think, like,

00:56:09.520 --> 00:56:12.159
the spending a lot of time on data processing,

00:56:14.879 --> 00:56:20.159
taking that just as an example, that is sometimes, like, the hard part, the complex part,

00:56:20.159 --> 00:56:25.280
the part that, like, requires actually still a lot of the data science skill set of understanding

00:56:25.919 --> 00:56:32.399
how do I shape this data in a way that, like, because I do understand the stats,

00:56:32.399 --> 00:56:37.439
because I do understand the algorithm, how do I, like, structure this problem in a way

00:56:37.439 --> 00:56:42.239
that the algorithm can understand the problem? And, like, at the end of the day, I think

00:56:43.040 --> 00:56:47.760
it's a funny conceit that in school we spend most of our time learning, like,

00:56:47.760 --> 00:56:54.560
hyperparameter tuning and typing that, like, model.fit, model.predict. That often isn't the

00:56:54.560 --> 00:56:59.520
hard part or sometimes even, like, the most interesting part, so I think being open with

00:56:59.520 --> 00:57:04.239
that, like, kind of growth mindset of, like, whatever job you end up in, there's going to

00:57:04.239 --> 00:57:08.479
be, like, a ton to learn and a ton of really interesting work to be done.

00:57:10.959 --> 00:57:18.320
Thank you. So I do understand that it's more about the company having a good data culture, and

00:57:20.000 --> 00:57:25.120
that way I think you will be able to have more chances of maximizing your learning.

00:57:25.679 --> 00:57:30.479
Yeah, for sure. The culture always matters so much.

